# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conservation-dependent-species
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx (*Oryx leucoryx*), also called the white oryx, was extinct in the wild as of 1972, but was reintroduced to the wild starting in 1982.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial reintroduction was primarily from two herds: the "World Herd" originally started at the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 from only nine oryx and the Saudi Arabian herd started in 1986 from private collections and some "World Herd" stock by the Saudi National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan, and as of 2013 the IUCN Red List classifies the species as vulnerable.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx was known to be in decline since the early 1900s in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By the 1930, there were two separate populations isolated from each other.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Talbot reported that Arabian oryx appeared to be extinct in its former range along the southern edge of Ar-Rub' al-Khali.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] He believed that any oryx still existing would be exterminated within the next few years and recommended that a captive breeding program be started to save the species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Michael Crouch, then Assistant Adviser in the Eastern Aden Protectorate, drew attention to the fact that each spring, small groups of oryx still emerged onto the gravel plains in the northeast corner of the Protectorate, where he thought a capture attempt would be possible.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial plan of the Fauna and Flora Preservation Society was to establish a herd in Kenya where another species of oryx already lived and flourished.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Kenyan plan was dropped because of an outbreak of hoof-and-mouth disease, and the oryx destined for Kenya were shipped to the Phoenix Zoo instead.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There were originally four individuals captured and seven donated for this project.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four were captured in Aden (now Yemen) near the border of Oman by an expedition led by the late Major Ian Grimwood, then chief game warden of Kenya, with help from Manahil and Mahra tribesmen.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] One male from this group later died of capture stress.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The seven donated oryx were: one from the London Zoo, two from Sheikh Jaber Abdullah al-Sabah, and two pairs from the collection of King Saud bin Abdul Aziz.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Five Arabian oryx were delivered to the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 (four in June and one in September).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A baby was born to the herd in October 1963 from a conception en route and another was born in spring 1964, bringing the starting population of the Phoenix Zoo herd to seven.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four oryx donated by King Saud arrived at the Phoenix Zoo in July 1964, bringing the population of the "World Herd" to 11.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The breeding program at the Phoenix Zoo was very successful, and the zoo celebrated its 225th Arabian oryx birth in 2002.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] From Phoenix, individuals were sent to other zoos and parks (including the San Diego Wild Animal Park) to start their herds.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Most of the Arabian oryx in the wild today have ancestors from the Phoenix Zoo.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroductions started in 1982 in Oman.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time, populations in the United Arab Emirates and Jordan are still not considered in the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) Red List wild oryx count.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The population in Oman is still receiving supplementary forage, and the introduction into Jordan was after the last update of the Red List.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 1980, the number of Arabian oryx in captivity had increased to the point that reintroduction to Oman was attempted from the San Diego Wild Animal Park to Jaaluni in the Jiddat al-Harasis.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The oryx were initially kept in large pens outdoors, but were released to the wild on January 31, 1982, in the Omani Central Desert and Coastal Hills.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These oryx became the core of the Oman herd in the wild, though there were several other releases of captive bred animals over the next two decades.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The area of their release became the Arabian Oryx Sanctuary.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] On June 28, 2007, Oman's Arabian Oryx Sanctuary was the first site to be removed from the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] UNESCO cited the Omani government's decision to open 90% of the site to oil prospecting as the main reason for this decision.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx population on the site has been reduced from 450 oryx in 1996 to only 65 in 2007, mostly due to poaching and illegal live capture.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There are now fewer than four breeding pairs left on the site.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Organized captive breeding of the Arabian oryx in Saudi Arabia began in April 1986, when 57 oryx from the farm of the late King Khalid bin Abdul Aziz in King Khalid Wildlife Research Center were brought to the National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC) near At-Ta'if.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Between the initial 1986 founding and 1996, 33 additional oryx (including some from the "World Herd") have been introduced to the founder generation of Arabian oryx at the NWRC.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since 1996, all additions to the population have been through births.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Due to an outbreak of *Mycobacterium bovis* (bovine tuberculosis) in the founder generation, a "buffer generation" was introduced in the herd.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since then, calves produced by the founder herd are removed from their dam immediately after birth and hand-reared.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These hand-reared second generation oryx are regularly tested for tuberculosis and a variety of other pathogenic agents, and join the breeding nucleus only when tests are consecutively negative.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] After breeding, they produce the third generation of oryx, which are tuberculosis free and mother-reared, and of which more than 80% are reintroduced into the wild.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroduction of a wild population began in 1995 in the 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid Protected Area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reserve covers about 12,000 km2 (4,600 sq mi) at the western edge of the Rubʿ al-Khali desert or "Empty Quarter".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at 160 individuals.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A free ranging herd was established in the newly created Mahazat as-Sayd Protected Area in 1989.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This 2,244 km2 (866 sq mi) fenced reserve is home to reintroduced oryx, gazelle and the houbara bustard.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at about 800 individuals.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In Israel the reintroduction program was established in 1978 when four pairs of Arabian oryx were purchased.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time the IUCN Redbook reported wild populations totaling 90–100 animals in three locations in Northern Arava and the Negev Desert.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2014 there are around 130 animals in the Aravah, and in 2013 they began to spread to the central Negev and the population keeps increasing.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In addition to the natural population increase, every year around six animals are released to the wild in Israel.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Israel is the only country in which the Arabian oryx was reintroduced where poaching prohibition can be enforced, and because of this the Israeli population grows annually.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Apart from the wild oryx population in Israel, there are a few dozen oryx in the Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve, a few breeding couples in the Jerusalem Biblical Zoo and a small herd in the Ramat Gan Safari.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction of oryx in Israel is one of a few successful programs reintroducing animals into nature in Israel; others include the introduction of the Persian onager (a proxy for the extinct Syrian onager), and the very successful reintroduction of Persian fallow deer.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In the early 1960s, the late Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan directed the capture of two breeding pairs of the oryx for the nucleus of a captive-breeding program in Al Ain, which would lead to the formation of the city's zoo.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2007 the United Arab Emirates started releasing animals into Umm Al Zumul.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been about 100 animals released.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As part of this initiative, a similar program is being developed to reintroduce this extinct species into its natural habitats in Yemen and Iraq.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since March 1999, the Emirate of Abu Dhabi has been host to an inter-governmental body known as The Coordinating Committee for the Conservation of the Arabian Oryx, which oversees the coordination of conservation efforts for this species within the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2012, GSCAO carried out an Arabian Oryx Disease Survey which was funded by the Environment Agency – Abu Dhabi (EAD), in the range states.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx are periodically released in protected areas, such as the Qasr Al Sarab Protected Area.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2017, it is estimated that around 10,000 Arabian oryx, of which 5,000 are estimated to be in Abu Dhabi, are currently in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction project for Jordan began when the Environment Agency of Abu Dhabi (EAD) and the Al Aqaba Special Economic Zone Authority signed a sponsorship agreement in April 2007.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Under this agreement, EAD is sponsoring the million three-year project which includes reintroduction of the Arabian oryx into the Wadi Rum Protected Area, rehabilitating the habitat, and helping local residents to improve their living standards.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Twenty oryx (12 males and 8 females) were released into the Wadi Rum Protected Area in July 2009.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 1986, as a result of the reintroduction efforts, the IUCN re-listed the Arabian oryx from extinct in the wild to endangered.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 2009, the Arabian oryx was protected by law in all areas where it appears.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In June 2011, the Arabian oryx was re-listed as vulnerable by the IUCN Red List.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2016 the IUCN estimated there were more than 1000 Arabian oryx in the wild, with 6000–7000 held in captivity worldwide in zoos, preserves, and private collections.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Some of these are in large fenced enclosures (free-roaming), including those in Syria (Al Talila), Bahrain, Qatar, and UAE.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This is the first time the IUCN has re-classified a species as vulnerable after it had been listed as extinct in the wild.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx is also listed in CITES Appendix I.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] The species primarily feeds on plant material and typically nests in large groups on beaches.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Due to hunting of adults, collecting of their eggs, pollution, habitat loss, and dams, the Arrau turtle is seriously threatened.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Arrau turtles are found in the Amazon, Orinoco and Essequibo basins in Brazil, Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, Venezuela and Guyana.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] On occasion, typically after floods, individuals turn up in Trinidad.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] They are found in deep rivers, ponds, freshwater lagoons and flooded forest in white-, black- and clear-water.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Arrau turtles can reach up to 90 kg (200 lb) in weight and the carapace length is up to 1.07 m (3.5 ft).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Most individuals are considerably smaller with the average adult female having a carapace length of 64–71 cm (2.1–2.3 ft) and the average adult male 40–50 cm (1.3–1.6 ft).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] In addition to an overall smaller size, males can be recognized by their longer tail and straighter carapace than the females.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Arrau turtles are brown, gray or olive-green, but the exact color varies depending on the algae growing on the carapace.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Adult Arrau turtles feed almost entirely on plant material such as fruits, seeds, leaves, legumes and algae, but may also take freshwater sponges, eggs and carcasses of dead animals (such as dead fish).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Captives have been recorded feeding on meat.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Juveniles feed on fish and plant material.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] The species is mainly active during the day.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] When nearing the breeding season, Arrau turtles migrate to certain sites where the eggs are laid.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] In some locations, nesting occurs in large groups on beaches, which reduces the risk posed by predators.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Some beaches have as many as 500 nesting females.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] During and just before the nesting season the species frequently basks, typically in groups.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] It is suspected that the additional heat accelerates the ovulation in the females.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] At other times the species is generally not found on land.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] When on land, it is usually very shy and retreats to the water at the slightest hint of danger.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] The female lays an average of 75–123 eggs (average varies depending on region), which are placed during the night in a 60–80 cm (2.0–2.6 ft) deep nest that is dug on the beach.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] The eggs are laid during the low water season and hatch as the water starts to rise.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] If it rises too fast or too early, the nest is flooded and the young die within the eggs.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] As long as nests are not dug up by predators, the hatching success rate is usually high, averaging at 83%.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] The eggs hatch after about 50 days and the sex of the young depends on the nest temperature (females at higher temperatures, males at lower).
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] When hatching, the young are around 5 cm (2 in) long and dart directly for the water, but they emerge to the attentions of many predators so that only about five percent ever reach the adult feeding grounds.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] When hatching, the females emit sounds which attract the young; they stay together for a period in the flooded forests.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] They can reach an age of 20 years or more in the wild, and captives have lived for at least 25 years.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Based on certain scientific models it has been estimated that the largest individuals perhaps are as old as 80 years.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] The species is slow to mature; some have suggested that females reach maturity when 4–8 years old and others have suggested about 17 years old.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Their social behavior, especially at certain nesting beaches, makes them and their eggs vulnerable to humans.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] In addition to being used for food, they are sometimes used in traditional medicine.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] At the main known nesting beaches, it is estimated that the number of nests fell from 34,000 in 1963 to 4,700 in 1981.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] In the middle Orinoco River alone, it is estimated that as many as 330,000 nested in 1800, but less than half this number nested in 1945 and by the early 2000s (decade) it had fallen to 700–1300.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] In addition to hunting and collecting of their eggs, threats include pollution, habitat loss, and dams, which can cause flooding of nest sites.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Several countries in their range have implemented laws protecting the species, but hunting and egg collection (even if illegal) continues.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] A number of conservation projects have been initiated.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] All species in the genus *Podocnemis* are listed on CITES Appendix II.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] The slow growth limits its potential for major commercial turtle farming.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/arrau-turtle] Nevertheless, about 880,000 turtles of various species were kept at 92 farms (both ones that are commercial and ones with conservation purpose) in 2004 in Brazil alone, and some of these keep Arrau turtles, also in semi-intensive farm systems.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] The most effective way to implement ANR is very site-specific, and many nations provide guidebooks on how to select and maintain an ANR project.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR is a common practice in many Asian countries.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] This method of protection has been used on *Imperata* grasslands in the Philippines for over three decades, as well as in China for more than five decades.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] According to the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), China has since 1999 funded extensive ANR in an effort to prevent soil corrosion in particular.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] Also the FAO reports that ANR is a common practice in Thailand.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR is gaining popularity as global climate change becomes a growing concern.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR has typically been used most often in tropical forests, however, it is now being used to help restore forested areas across all ecosystem types.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] A wide variety of conditions are required to optimally implement ANR and ensure successful regeneration.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] One involves a sufficient density of naturally regenerated seedlings, though the specific density required is dependent on specific factors, such as, distribution, species composition, growth rates, soil fertility, etc.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] A density range of 200 to 800 seedlings per hectare has been suggested to ensure optimal regeneration.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] The availability of seed sources from nearby remnant forests is necessary to serve as seed inputs for colonization of vegetation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] The control or removal of all disturbances (such as, grazing, fires, and logging) is also crucial.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] The practice of ANR has a wide range of benefits.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR focuses on reducing ecological barriers in order to accelerate natural regeneration and growth, rather than the planting of seedlings.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] This allows for a low-cost method that removes the expenses associated with site preparation and planting/raising seedlings themselves, which can be appealing in large-scale restoration projects.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] Another benefit involves job opportunities.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR requires high maintenance and can be labor-intensive, and involve methods of weeding, grass pressing, establishing and maintaining firebreaks, etc.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] This can ultimately help to create jobs and improve livelihoods in local and/or impoverished communities.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] However, if the forestation is not a positive change, for example, if the land is needed for food, the people of the community will be unlikely to get involved and produce successful ANR.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] Carbon sequestration, biodiversity enrichment and recovery are just a few environmental benefits ANR provides, which can help improve ecosystems and mitigate climate change.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR focuses on native species and natural succession of existing vegetation, which ensures that plant communities and inhabiting wildlife are maintained and are not disturbed.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] A **conservation-dependent species** is a species which has been categorized as "**Conservation Dependent**" ("**LR/cd**") by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), as dependent on conservation efforts to prevent it from becoming endangered.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] A species that is reliant on the conservation attempts of humans is considered conservation dependent.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Such species must be the focus of a continuing species-specific and/or habitat-specific conservation program, the cessation of which would result in the species qualifying for one of the threatened categories within a period of five years.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] The determination of status is constantly monitored and can change.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] This category is part of the IUCN 1994 Categories & Criteria (version 2.3), which is no longer used in evaluation of taxa, but persists in the IUCN Red List for taxa evaluated prior to 2001, when version 3.1 was first used.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Using the 2001 (version 3.1) system these taxa are classed as near threatened, but those that have not been re-evaluated remain with the "Conservation Dependent" category.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Conservation-dependent species require maintenance additional to the use of the United States Endangered Species Act of 1973.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] This act is said to protect species from extinction by concerns and acts of conservation.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Conservation-dependent species rely on population connectivity between humans and animals to maintain their life.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Connectivity is based in regard to the federal regulatory provisions that protect the species and its habitat.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Habitats and species are difficult to conserve when they are not susceptible to the regulations put in place.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] It is also seen that laws and acts have flaws that cause gaps in their motive.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] The Endangered Species Act fails to account for biological ecosystem conservation and threats to a species presence.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Conservation in these conditions causes data gaps and leads to the depletion of species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Funding of the federal provisions show to be a major concern when efforts are being made to conserve species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Legal members who don't agree on where funding should go cause more harm to the conservation-dependent species by making no effort for restoration.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Despite legal efforts for defining a restoration program and setting regulatory provisions, conservation-dependent species are still in danger.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] While conservation dependent plants and animals fall under the same risk status in the environment different methods are used to protect them.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Conservation dependent animals are typically protected by recovery plans and agreements for conservation by the government.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Plants that are conservation dependent have less protection behind them as the major method for conservation is keeping a habitat healthy.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] In order to do so, keeping areas uncivilized and minimizing pollution emissions are predictable solutions.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Keeping the flora (plants) and fauna (animals) in their region out of the conservation dependent category is the main goal of these methods.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Species that were considered Conservation Dependent were under the lower risk category of status in the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] The category of species may change when reassessed.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] From 2020, some IUCN Red List species assessments began to optionally include a "Green Status", which is a standardized assessment of the global recovery of the species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] This assessment reintroduces a systematic "Conservation Dependence" measure to the Red List, but is now separate to the assessed category of the species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] The metric compares calculated scores for the short-term (10 years) future of a species with and without conservation actions.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] This metric allows recognition of species whose current conservation status is dependent on continued conservation actions.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] The Green Status assessment is an optional part of a IUCN Red List species assessment.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] It provides a global standard for measuring species recovery and assessing conservation impact.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] In fisheries around the world, there is a list of rules that people must follow which are in place as a conservation effort.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] These rules protect the conservation dependent listing of Scalloped Hammerhead shark (Sphyrna lewini) under the EPBC Act is one major step for conservation of endangered species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Examples of conservation-dependent species include the California ground cricket.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] As of December 2015, there remains 209 conservation-dependent plant species and 29 conservation-dependent animal species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] As of January 2026, the IUCN still lists 13 conservation-dependent animal species, and one conservation-dependent subpopulations or stocks.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] In Australia, the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 still uses a "Conservation Dependent" category for classifying fauna and flora species.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Species recognized as "Conservation Dependent" do not receive special protection, as they are not considered "matters of national environmental significance under the EPBC Act".
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Any assemblage of species may be listed as a "threatened ecological community" under the EPBC Act.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] Fauna may be classified under this category if its flora is directly threatened.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] The legislation uses categories similar to those of the *IUCN 1994 Categories & Criteria*.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] It does not, however, have a near threatened category or any other "lower risk" categories.
[src:conservation-dependent-species/conservation-dependent-species] No species of flora has been given the category under the EPBC Act.
